.TH FACIAL_CAPTURE 1 "2025-01" "pam_facial_auth" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
facial_capture \- capture face images for PAM facial authentication

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B facial_capture
\-u USER
[\-d DEVICE] [\-w WIDTH] [\-h HEIGHT]
[\-n FRAMES] [\-s MS] [\-f] [\-g] [\-v]
[\-c FILE]

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B facial_capture
utility captures face images using a webcam and stores them under
.BR /etc/pam_facial_auth/images/USER .
These images are later used by the facial recognition training tool.

The program uses OpenCV for webcam access and face detection.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-u, --user USER
User name for which images are captured. Required.

.TP
.B \-d, --device DEVICE
Video device (default:
/dev/video0).

.TP
.B \-w, --width WIDTH
Set capture width (default: 640).

.TP
.B \-h, --height HEIGHT
Set capture height (default: 480).

.TP
.B \-n, --frames N
Number of frames to capture (default: 5).

.TP
.B \-s, --sleep MS
Pause between frames in milliseconds (default: 500).

.TP
.B \-f, --force
Overwrite old images.

.TP
.B \-g, --nogui
Disable GUI preview windows.

.TP
.B \-v, --verbose
Enable verbose/debug logging.

.TP
.B \-c, --config FILE
Configuration file path (default:
/etc/security/pam_facial.conf).

.TP
.B --help
Show usage information.

.SH FILES
.TP
.B /etc/pam_facial_auth/
Base directory for images and models.
.TP
.B /etc/security/pam_facial.conf
Configuration file.

